{"parse":{"title":"state","pageid":8579,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|State|státe}}\n==English==\n{{wp|<dab!>}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*steh₂-}}\n{{etymon|en|id=polity|:inh|enm:stat<id:condition>|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|stat}} (as a noun); adopted c. 1200 from both {{der|en|fro|estat}} and {{der|en|la|stātus||manner of standing, attitude, position, carriage, manner, dress, apparel; and other senses}}, from {{m|la|stō|stāre|to stand}}. {{doublet|en|estate|status}}. The sense of \"polity\" develops in the 14th century. Compare {{cog|fr|être}}, {{cog|el|στέω}}, {{cog|it|stare}}, {{cog|pt|estar}}, {{cog|ro|sta}}, and {{cog|es|estar}}. The verb is first attested around the beginning of the 16th century. Related to {{cog|en|stand}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/steɪt/|a=RP,GA}}\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-state.ogg|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-state.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{rhymes|en|eɪt|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|condition}} A [[condition]]; a [[set]] of [[circumstance]]s applying at any given [[time]].\n#: {{uxi|en|a '''state''' of being}}\n#: {{uxi|en|a '''state''' of emergency}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1697|tlr=w:John Dryden|chapter=[[w:Aenid|Æneis]]|title=The Works of {{w|Virgil}}|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzIJAAAAQAAJ|volume=III|location=Londo|publisher=w:Jacob Tonson|year_published=1721|page=713|passage=Relate what ''Latium'' was, her ancient Kings : / Declare the paſt, and preſent '''State''' of things, / When firſt the ''Trojan'' Fleet ''Auſonia'' ſought ; / And how the Rivals lov’d, and how they fought.}}\n#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=8|passage=I corralled the judge, and we started off across the fields, in no very mild '''state''' of fear of that gentleman's wife, whose vigilance was seldom relaxed.}}\n## {{lb|en|physics}} A [[complete]] [[description]] of a [[system]], consisting of [[parameter]]s that determine all [[property|properties]] of the system.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1977|author=J. B. Sykes; {{w|John Stewart Bell}}, translating {{w|Lev Landau}}; w:Evgeny Lifshitz|title={{w|Course of Theoretical Physics}} Vol. 3: Quantum Mechanics: Non-relativistic Theory|page=28\n|passage='''States''' in which the energy has definite values are called ''stationary states'' of a system; they are described by wave functions Ψₙ which are the eigenfunctions of the Hamiltonian operator, i.e. which satisfy the equation ''ĤΨₙ = EₙΨₙ'', where ''Eₙ'' are the eigenvalues of the energy.}}\n## {{senseid|en|bad condition}} {{lb|en|colloquial|in singular}} A [[mess]]; [[disorder]]; a bad condition or set of circumstances.\n##: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:difficult situation}}\n##: {{coi|en|[[absolute state|absolute '''state''']]}}\n##: {{coi|en|[[in a state|in a '''state''']]}}\n##: {{coi|en|in a bit of a '''state'''}}\n##* {{RQ:Welsh Trainspotting|page=92|chapter=Traditional Sunday Breakfast|passage=Who the fuck undressed me? Try tracing back. It's now Sunday. Yesterday was Saturday. The semi-final at Hampden. I had got myself into some fucking '''state''' before and after the match.}}\n##* {{quote-web|en|url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jun/03/trump-windsor-state-visit-queen|title=An absolute state of a visit: what the Trump and Windsor snapshots tell us|author=Hannah Jane Parkinson|date=2019-06-03|work=The Guardian|passage=An absolute '''state''' of a visit: what the Trump and Windsor snapshots tell us [title]}}\n## {{lb|en|computing}} The [[stable]] condition of a [[processor]] during a particular [[clock]] [[cycle]].\n##: {{ux|en|In the fetch '''state''', the address of the next instruction is placed on the address bus.}}\n## {{lb|en|computing}} The set of all parameters relevant to a [[computation]].\n##: {{ux|en|The '''state''' here includes a set containing all names seen so far.}}\n## {{lb|en|computing}} The [[value#Noun|value]]s of all parameters at some point in a computation.\n##: {{ux|en|A debugger can show the '''state''' of a program at any breakpoint.}}\n## {{lb|en|sciences}} The [[physical]] property of [[matter]] as [[solid]], [[liquid]], [[gas]] or [[plasma]].\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} Highest and [[stationary]] condition, as that of [[maturity]] between [[growth]] and [[decline]], or as that of [[crisis]] between the [[increase]] and the [[abating]] of a [[disease]]; [[height]]; [[acme]].\n# High [[social standing]] or circumstance.\n## [[pomp|Pomp]], [[ceremony]], or [[dignity]].\n##: {{coi|en|[[in state|in '''state''']]}}\n##: {{ux|en|The President's body will [[lie in state|lie in '''state''']] at the Capitol.}}\n## [[rank|Rank]]; [[condition]]; [[quality]].\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Richard 3|I|iii|text=And leſned by that ſmall, God I beſeech him, / Thy honor, '''ſtate,''' and ſeate, is due to me.}}\n## Condition of [[prosperity]] or [[grandeur]]; [[wealthy]] or [[prosperous]] circumstances; [[social]] [[importance]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1616|author=w:Francis Bacon|title=The History of Henry VII, of England|year_published=1786|page=139|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFrjxrwTS-MC&pg=PA139|passage=Firſt, in princely behaviour and geſture, teaching him how he ſhould keep of a kind of '''ſtate,''' and yet, with a modeſt ſenſe of his misfortunes.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1703|tlr=w:Alexander Pope|chapter=The [[w:Thebaid (Latin poem)|Thebais]] of {{w|Statius}}|title=The Works of Alexander Pope|volume=II|section=book I|location=London|publisher=H. Lintont et al.|year_published=1751|page=145|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=r0UVAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145|passage=Can this imperious lord forget to reign, / Quit all his '''ſtate,''' deſcend, and ſerve again ?}}\n## A [[chair]] with a [[canopy]] above it, often standing on a [[dais]]; a [[seat]] of [[dignity]]; also, the canopy itself.\n##: {{syn|en|chair of state}}\n##* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=X|lines=443–447|passage={{...}}and from the dore / Of that ''Plutonia'' Hall, inviſible / Aſcended his high Throne, which under '''ſtate''' / Of richeſt texture ſpred, at th’ upper end / Was plac’t in regal luſtre.|year=1873}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1712|author=w:John Arbuthnot; {{w|Jonathan Swift}} [uncertain]|chapter=Jack’s Charms, or the Method by which he gain’d Peg’s Heart|title=John Bull Still In His Senses|location=London|publisher=John Morphew|page=13|pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/johnbullstillinh00arbu#page/n16|passage=He invented a way of coming into a Room backwards, which he ſaid ſhew’d more Humility, and leſs Affectation ; where other People ſtood, he ſat ; when he went to Court, he us’d to kick away the '''State,''' and ſit down by his Prince, Cheek by [[jowl|Choul]]{{...}}}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[great]] [[person]], a [[dignitary]]; a [[lord]] or [[prince]].\n##* {{RQ:Marlowe Tamburlaine|part=1|scene=i|page=19|passage=We in the name of other Perſean '''ſtates''',<br>And commons of this mightie Monarchy,<br>Preſent thee with the Emperiall Diadem.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1644|author=w:John Milton|title=w:Areopagitica|page=1\n|passage=They who to '''States''' and Governours of the Commonwealth direct their Speech, High Court of Parlament, or wanting ſuch acceſſe in a private condition, write that which they foreſee may advance the publick good ; I ſuppoſe them as at the beginning of no meane endeavour, not a little alter’d and mov’d inwardly in their mindes{{...}}}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[estate|Estate]], [[possession]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1595|author=w:Samuel Daniel|editor=w:Alexander Balloch Grosart|chapter=The Civile Wars between the Two Houses of Lancaster and Yorke|title=The Complete Works in Verse and Prose of Samuel Daniel|volume=II|section=book IV, stanza 20|page=142|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=hdQUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA142|passage=Their parties great, meanes good, the ſeaſon fit, / Their practice cloſe, their faith ſuſpected not, / Their '''ſtates''' far off, and they of wary wit : / Who, with large promiſes, ſo wooe the Scot / To aide their Cauſe, as he conſents to it ; / And glad was to diſturne that furious ſtreame / Of warre, on vs, that elſe had ſwallowed them.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=c. 1619|author=w:Philip Massinger; w:Nathan Field|chapter=w:The Fatal Dowry|title=The Works of Philip Massinger|volume=II|location=London|publisher=T. Davies|year_published=1761|section=[Act V, scene ii]|page=271|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LznuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA271|passage=Your '''’State,''' my Lord, again is yours.}}\n# {{senseid|en|polity, community}} A [[polity]] or [[community]].\n## {{lb|en|historically|_|often|capitalized}} A [[sovereign]] [[country]] or [[city state]], with the [[central government]] acting as its visible [[instrument]].\n##* {{ante|1949}}, {{w|Albert Einstein}}, as quoted by Virgil Henshaw in ''Albert Einstein: Philosopher Scientist'' (1949)\n##*: Never do anything against conscience even if the '''state''' demands it.\n## A [[political]] [[division]] of a [[federation]] [[retain]]ing a [[notable]] [[degree]] of [[autonomy]], as in the [[United States]], [[Mexico]], [[Nigeria]], or [[India]].\n##: {{ux|en|His alibi is that he was out of '''state''' the night of the murder.}}\n##* {{quote-book\n|en\n|year=1789\n|title=w:United States Bill of Rights\n|text=The powers not delegated to the United States by the Constitution, nor prohibited by it to the '''States''', are reserved to the '''States''' respectively, or to the people.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en |year=1839 |title=The public statute laws of the state of Connecticut|author=John Beach; Thomas Clap Perkins |page=35|ISBN=|passage=You do solemnly swear (or affirm, as the case may be) that you will support the constitution of the United States, and the constitution of the '''state''' of Connecticut, so long as you continue a citizen thereof; and that you will faithfully discharge, according to law, the duties of the office of {{...}} to the best of your abilities.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en |year=1993|title=Vertical fiscal imbalance and the assignment of taxing powers in Australia|author=Charles E. McLure |page=|ISBN=0817954538|passage=As Australia considers whether to allow '''states''' greater latitude in the indirect tax field, it must ask what it will do when (not if) it finally decides that the federal government should enact a modern general sales tax.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en |year=2001|title=The Impact of Geology on the United States|author=Angus Macleod Gunn |page=0313314446|ISBN=|passage=The Central Lowlands is often referred to as the heart of America — and with good reason: If we look at the names of the eight '''states''' with populations of 10 million or more, this region has three of them, Illinois, Ohio, and Michigan, more than any one of the other five.}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} A form of government other than a [[monarchy]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1662|author=w:John Dryden|chapter=Satire on the Dutch|title=The Works of the English Poets|volume=XIII|location=London|publisher=R. Hett|year_published=1779|page=41|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=G2uDelidtooC&pg=PA41|passage=Well monarchies may own religion’s name, / But '''ſtates''' are atheiſts in their very frame.}}\n## {{lb|en|anthropology}} A [[society]] larger than a [[tribe]]. A society large enough to form a state in the sense of a government.\n# {{lb|en|mathematics|stochastic processes}} An [[element]] of the [[range]] of the [[random variable]]s that define a [[random]] [[process]].\n# {{sid|en|aspect}} {{lb|en|grammar|semantics}} The [[lexical aspect]] ([[aktionsart]]) of [[verb]]s or [[predicate]]s that do not change over time.\n#: {{antonyms|en|occurrence}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1997|author=Robert van Valin; Randy LaPolla|title=Syntax|page=92|text={{...}}distinctions among states of affairs are reflected to a striking degree in distinctions among ''Aktionsart'' types. That is, situations are expressed by '''state''' verbs or predicates, events by achievement verbs or predicates, and actions by activity verbs or predicates.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DxcrbgT1_oMC&pg=PA92}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Nick Riemer|title=Introducing Semantics|page=320|text=The most basic Aktionsart distinction is between '''states''' and occurrences.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tJjZ0FmNdzIC&pg=PA320}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col4|en|absolute state|confessional state|Part A state|Part B state|Part C state\n|Bayou State\n|Bear State\n|Bell state\n|Big Bend State\n|Blackwater State\n|Blue Hen State\n|blue state\n|bound state\n|buffer state\n|cat state\n|Chinook State\n|city state\n|client state\n|cluster state\n|continental state\n|convention state\n|Cracker State\n|Creole State\n|deep state\n|Ecclesiastical State\n|end state\n|excited state\n|failed state\n|federal state\n|feudatory state\n|Flower State\n|flyover state\n|fugue state\n|free state\n|garrison state\n|Gem State\n|graph state\n|green state\n|ground state|Hawaii State|State of Hawaii\n|hole state\n|iron state\n|link state\n|Lumber State\n|member state\n|nanny state\n|narco state\n|night watchman state\n|Papal States\n|party state\n|police state\n|prerogative state\n|princely state\n|pseudostate\n|puppet state\n|purple state|normative state\n|quantum state\n|red state| federated state|general state\n|rogue state\n|rump state\n|save state\n|sea state\n|solid state\n|sovereign state\n|steady state\n|swing state\n|transition state\n|unitary state\n|upstate\n|vassal state\n|wait state\n|welfare state|character state|warfare state\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|Hospitality State|Islamic State in Iraq and Syria|Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Kachin State|Mon State|Rakhine State|Shan State|State of Mexico|quantum state tomography|state examination\n|all-state|anthrostate|antistate|bistate|bitstate|costate|counterstate|downstate|eigenstate|ethnostate|geostate|immunostate|instate|interstate|intrastate|macrostate|megastate|mesostate|metastate|microstate|mindstate|ministate|multistate|narcostate|nonstate|outstate|annexed state|outlaw state|parastate|petrostate|polystate|prestate|prostate|protostate|quasistate|savestate|semistate|statal|State of Mississippi|statechart|statecraft|statedom|statefinder|stateful|statefunction|statehouse|stateless|statelike|stateling|statemate|statemonger|stateprison|stater|stateroom|statescraft|stateship|statesperson|stateswoman|statevector|statewide|statewise|statie|statism|statist|statocracy|statoid|statolatry|substate|superstate|suprastate|technostate|tristate|typestate|aspirant state\n|battleground state\n|bedroom state\n|bellwether state\n|border state\n|chain-melted state\n|change of state\n|chief of state\n|circular state|Jewish state|state law\n|civilization-state\n|collaborationist state\n|construct state\n|deep state\n|Dervish state|State Union of Serbia and Montenegro\n|determinate state\n|echo state network\n|Efimov state\n|emphatic state|area state|state police officer\n|enemy of the state\n|ephemeral state\n|Esdaile state\n|ethno-state\n|fifty-first state\n|fifty-state strategy\n|finite-state automaton\n|finite-state machine\n|finite state machine\n|flag state\n|flow state\n|Fock state\n|fugue state\n|Gibbs state\n|governed state\n|great office of state\n|Hartle-Hawking state\n|head of state\n|home state\n|identical by state\n|in a real state\n|in a right state\n|in a state\n|indeterminate state\n|in-state\n|in state\n|Kievan state\n|kin state\n|Kyivan state\n|liquid state machine\n|mafia state\n|minimal state\n|minister of state\n|narco-state\n|nation-state\n|nation state\n|network state\n|New York state\n|night-watchman state\n|nominal state\n|non-state\n|non-state actor\n|non state actor\n|organ of state\n|out-of-state\n|oxidation state\n|persistent vegetative state\n|persistive vegetative state\n|physical state\n|prison state\n|pronominal state\n|pro-state\n|pseudostate\n|pseudo-state\n|rentier state\n|representational state transfer\n|re-state\n|Rydberg state\n|salute st